PART II — MERSEL BRAND ATTRIBUTION ADDENDUM (English translation, for reference)
================================================================================

This Addendum is an "additional term" attached by the Licensor under
the authority of the last paragraph of Section 4 of the Apache License
2.0 above (the "Brand Attribution Addendum" or "Addendum"). The
Addendum forms a single instrument together with the Apache License;
in the event of any conflict, the Turkish text in Part II above shall
prevail.

PREAMBLE — RATIONALE AND CONSIDERATION
--------------------------------------

Türkiye's domestic e-signature ecosystem — smart card drivers, PKCS#11
modules, TÜBİTAK-ESYA bindings, the Revenue Administration's (GİB)
e-Document integration, e-Invoice enrolment workflows, and qualified
certificate validation infrastructure — has historically been
surrounded by proprietary vendors offering expensive, closed-source
products. For SMEs, independent CPAs, developers, and enterprise
integrators, an open-source, royalty-free, auditable, and
TÜBİTAK-ESYA-independent alternative has long been absent.

To address this structural gap, Mersel DSS has developed the Mersel
DSS Agent Signer project as a public-interest, open-source
contribution to the ecosystem, including a PKCS#11 reflection layer,
low-level smart-card type detection (ATR + library matching),
PIN-less public certificate listing, PAdES-B / XAdES-BES / XAdES
Counter-Signature generation, GİB e-Invoice enrolment integration,
and a local certificate-chain validation stack — collectively
delivering, for the first time at this scope, a systemic "commons"
to the field. The contribution makes available to the entire Turkish
software community the cumulative engineering effort, capital, and
multi-year domain knowledge that would otherwise be required to
rebuild an equivalent solution from scratch.

The Software is distributed under a permissive base license (Apache
2.0), which permits anyone — natural or legal person, commercial or
academic — to integrate the Software into closed-source products,
monetize it, and even offer it as a hosted service (SaaS). This
permissiveness is a deliberate choice by Mersel DSS; the Software
is designed as shared open infrastructure rather than as part of
the closed ecosystem approach taken by incumbent cloud vendors.

As reasonable consideration for this generosity, the Licensor
requests the preservation of three small user-interface elements
that make the upstream contributor visible: the "MERSEL DSS" brand
mark in the splash window, the banner in the main window, and the
mersel.io attribution line in the footer. These elements are not
merely symbolic recognition of the Licensor; they also serve:

   (i)   to prevent provenance ambiguity in the open-source
         value chain,

   (ii)  to keep the vulnerability-disclosure channel one click
         away from every end user,

   (iii) to maintain a healthy and verifiable reference point in
         Türkiye's e-signature ecosystem,

   (iv)  to preserve the public visibility of the cumulative
         work Mersel DSS has invested in the ecosystem, and

   (v)   to safeguard the end user's transparent answer to
         "who built this software and whom can I trust?".

This Addendum, together with Apache License 2.0, forms a
CONTRACTUAL BALANCE: You (the licensee) receive the right to use
all copyright, patent, and distribution rights in the Software FREE
OF CHARGE and on PERMISSIVE terms; the Licensor in turn requests
only a proportionate VISIBILITY consideration, strictly limited to
three small user-interface elements. This balance is the essential
cause and reasonable consideration of the agreement; by beginning
to use the Software, the licensee is deemed to have accepted this
balance.

The obligation to preserve the Brand Notices applies
UNCONDITIONALLY to every reproduction, distribution, modification,
or other use of the Software. Renaming the Software, distributing
it under your own brand, or embedding it inside another product
does not extinguish or reduce this obligation. Parties who modify
the Software must, in addition to preserving the Brand Notices,
comply with the Modification Disclosure obligations under
Section 3 so that the end user can see the change and understand
that the responsibility for the modification lies with the
distributor.

